3 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 427.14b), is amended to read as follows:
4 Section 427.14b. A. Beginning January 1, 2024, the Oklahoma
5 Medical Marijuana Authority shall require employees of a medical
6 marijuana business licensee to apply for and receive a credential
7 authorizing the employee to work in a licensed medical marijuana
8 business.
9 B. The Authority may contract with one or more third-party
10 vendors to provide the credentialing services necessary to carry out
11 the provisions of this section.
12 C. The Authority shall determine the services to be provided by
13 such third-party vendor and shall establish costs and prices. If
14 contracted for credentialing services, a third-party vendor shall on
15 behalf of the Authority conduct the background checks and verify
16 eligibility for any employees of a medical marijuana business
17 license holder to obtain a credential.
18 D. Upon successful completion of the national fingerprint-based
19 background check conducted by the Oklahoma State Bureau of
20 Investigation within thirty (30) days prior to the application,
21 completion of the educational training required pursuant to the
22 provisions of this section, and verification of eligibility for an
23 employee, the Authority shall issue a credential to the employee.
24 The applicant shall submit proof of completion of the required
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1242 Page 24

1 educ ational training and results of the background check and
2 verification in the credential application, and the results of
3 background checks and verifications shall be provided to the
4 Authority by the third-party vendor.
5 E. Beginning January 1, 2027, in order to receive an employee
6 credential, all employees of a licensed medical marijuana business
7 shall annually complete an educational training course provided by
8 or approved by the Authority. The employee shall submit proof of
9 completion of the required educational training in order to receive
10 an employee credential. Such training may include an overview of
11 state statutes and administrative rules, patient privacy
12 requirements, and the safe handling and storage of medical
13 marijuana.
14 F. If the third-party vendor determines that an employee of a
15 medical marijuana business holder does not meet the minimum
16 statutory requirements for a credential, the applicant or employee
17 shall have no recourse against the third-party vendor but may appeal
18 such adverse determination to the Authority.
19 G. The To be approved by the Authority, the third-party vendor
20 shall not be civilly liable to an applicant, licensee, or employee
21 of a licensee for any acts taken in good-faith compliance with the
22 provisions of Section 420 et seq. of this title and the Oklahoma
23 Medical Marijuana and Patient Protection Act and the rules
24 promulgated by the Oklahoma Medical Marijuana Authority. provide an
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1242 Page 25

1 educ ational training course plan that includes, but is not limited
2 to, an overview of the following topics:
3 1. State statutes and administrative rules;
4 2. Patient privacy requirements;
5 3. Safe, sanitary handling and storage of medical marijuana;
6 4. Guidance and training on how to appropriately advise
7 patients on the use of medical marijuana products; and
8 5. Detecting, preventing, and reporting the diversion of
9 medical marijuana to minors, unlicensed medical marijuana patients
10 or unlicensed medical marijuana caregivers, or other unauthorized
11 persons.
12 G. A nonrefundable application fee of Five Hundred Dollars
13 ($500.00) shall be submitted with the educational training
14 application of the third-party vendor and a nonrefundable
15 application fee of Two Hundred Fifty Dollars ($250.00) shall be
16 required every twenty-four (24) months for renewal of said
17 application. A third-party vendor shall update the course with any
18 applicable changes to the Oklahoma Statutes or administrative rules
19 not later than ten (10) days after the effective date of the change.
20 The third-party vendor shall notify the Authority of a change to an
21 approved course not later than three (3) days after the change. The
22 educational training course may be taught in a classroom or virtual
23 setting and an employee of a licensed medical marijuana business
24 shall be required to score a seventy percent (70%) or higher on a
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1242 Page 26

1 post -course exam demonstrating an understanding of the course
2 materials.
3 H. 1. The Authority shall review the medical marijuana
4 credential application; approve, reject, or deny the application;
5 and send the approval, rejection, or denial letter to the applicant
6 by the same method in which the application was submitted to the
7 Authority.
8 2. Each approved applicant shall be issued a credential, which
9 shall act as proof of his or her approved status, to be worn or
10 displayed during the hours of work of the employee. Rejection and
11 denial letters shall provide a reason for the rejection or denial.
12 Applications may only be rejected or denied for failure to meet the
13 standards set forth in the provisions of the Oklahoma Medical
14 Marijuana and Patient Protection Act or rules promulgated by the
15 Executive Director of the Authority. If an application is rejected
16 for failure to provide required information, the applicant shall
17 have thirty (30) days to submit the required information for
18 reconsideration. Unless the Authority determines otherwise, an
19 application that has been resubmitted but is still incomplete or
20 contains errors that are not clerical or typographical in nature
21 shall be denied.
22 I. The Authority may approve any third-party vendor meeting the
23 requirements of subsection F of this section to provide the
24 educational training course necessary to carry out the provisions of
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1242 Page 27

1 subs ection E of this section. The Authority shall have sixty (60)
2 days to approve or deny an application of a vendor to provide the
3 educational training course.
4 J. The Executive Director of the Authority may promulgate rules
5 to implement the provisions of this section.
6 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
7 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 427.5b of Title 63, unless there
8 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
9 There is hereby created in the State Treasury a revolving fund
10 for the Oklahoma Medical Marijuana Authority to be designated the
11 “Oklahoma Medical Marijuana Land Reclamation Revolving Fund”. The
12 fund shall be a continuing fund, not subject to fiscal year
13 limitations, and shall consist of all monies received by the
14 Authority from land reclamation fees collected pursuant to the
15 Oklahoma Medical Marijuana and Patient Protection Act. All monies
16 accruing to the credit of the fund are hereby appropriated and may
17 be budgeted and expended by the Oklahoma Medical Marijuana Authority
18 for the purposes provided for in this section. Expenditures from
19 the fund shall be made upon warrants issued by the State Treasurer
20 against claims filed as prescribed by law with the Director of the
21 Office of Management and Enterprise Services for approval and
22 payment. Up to Five Million Dollars ($5,000,000.00) of the funds
23 received by and credited to the fund may be used and expended by the
24 Oklahoma Medical Marijuana Authority for environmental remediation
ENGR. H. A. to ENGR. S. B. NO. 1242 Page 28

1 and redevelopment projects. Any remaining funds shall be deposited
2 in the General Revenue Fund of the State Treasury.
3 SECTION 4. REPEALER Section 2, Chapter 41, O.S.L. 2023
4 (63 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 427.26), is hereby repealed.
5 SECTION 5. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026."
